Termination of a loop is established using a decreasing variant, also known as a ranking function. 
The decreasing variant may also need supporting inductive invariants for the proof of termination to be valid.
Provide the decreasing variant that proves the termination of the loop along with any supporting invariants that may be necessary.
Output all the loop invariants and variants in one code block. For example:
```
/*@ 
    loop invariant i1;
    loop invariant i2;
    loop variant v1;
*/
```

Use the ACSL syntax to provide the variant and invariants.

```
#define assume(e) if(!(e)) return 0;

extern int unknown(void);
extern int unknown_int(void);
extern unsigned int unknown_uint(void);
extern _Bool unknown_bool(void);
extern char unknown_char(void);
extern unsigned short unknown_ushort(void);



char* strchr(char* str, int c) {
	for (; *str != 0; ++str) {
		if (*str == c) {
			return str;
		}
	}
	return 0;
}

int main()
{
    char in[100];
    for( int i = 0 ; i < 99 ; i++ )
        in[i] = '\n';
    char* p = in;
    in[99] = 0;
    while( *p )
    {
        char* n =strchr( p , '\n');
        if( n == 0 )
            n = p + 99;
        p = n + 1;
    }
    return 0;
}

```
